{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_archer_ver01/data/sn86058053/00517017322/1958032801/0614.xml":{"full_text":"Rateren mm second class matter at toe foa\\ Office, uary, Indiana,\nmsder the met of Congress of March 8, 1879.\nme GAKl AMERICAN FUBLISHINCT CO.\n338 Weal 15th \u2018Avenue Gary, Indiana Phone 3-2041\naXLVitr O. WHITLOCK PabliSbei\nEDWINA H. WHITLOCK Editoi\nVOLUME XXX NO. 13 FRIDAY, MARCH 28, 1958\nUnder the Gavel\nMr.. and Mrs. Leonard Lap\naley and three children arrived\nthis week from Germany. On\ntheir |ray home they stopped in\nIreland, from there to New York\nand from there to Fort Benning,\nGeorgia where he was' discharged\nf)ie entire trip was made by\nplane, TWA. Mr. Lapsley is the\nson of Mrs. Erma Rogers and\ngrandsoil of Mr. and Mrs. Floyd\nHayes. They will be at home to\ntheir many friends at 2257\nAdam* street.\nThe Block Club of 2300\nWashington street met Monday\nnight in the home of Mr. and\nMrs. Oscar Winbush. The club\nmade plans to have waffle break\nfast in the home of Mrs. Mary\nWilliams, Thursday, April 10.\nBreakfast will be ready at 9\na.m. at 2335 Washington street.\n\nThe Five Point State tea given\nby Alpha Omega Chapter No.\nE3 OES, Sunday afternoon in\nthe newly decorated Masonic\nHall, 1813 Washington \"street\nwas an elaborate affair as well\nas educational.\nThe tea is one of the annual\nprograms given by the Chapter\neach year. This was the first\nproject of the worthy matron,\nMrs. Etta Barbee. The tea was\nsupervised by past worthy mat\nion Mrs. Millie I* Black. Each\npoint of the start represented a\nstate and gave the history of\nthe state and what he chief i\nproduction or manufacturing^ was\nnoted by thestate.\nMrs. Madeline Adams repre\nsented the State of Florida with\na table displaying Florida pro\nduction. Mrs. Bertha Evans re\npresented the State of California\nwith a beautiful display, Mrs.\nHattie Ligon, New York, Mrs.\n\u2022Hatie Tarenzer the State of\nWashington with displays and\nMrs.\" Mary F. Janies, the State\ncf Michigan.' All were very\ncolorful.\nThe American scheme of red,\nwhite and blue was carried out\nwith the singing of patriotic\nsongs. Mrs. F. James was queen,\nhaving raised the largest sum\nof money, Miss Joyce Carter\nwas the State\u2019s Sweetheart. Mrs.\nFlorence Gray was the musican\nlor the day.\nOne of the prettiest teas of\ntl-e season, was the one given by\nthe Nurses Guild of Mary Cruitup\nChapter No. 48 OES, held in the\nlovely home of the worthy mat\nron, Mrs. Essie Sims, 2701\nHarrison boulevar,d Sunday af\nternoon. The many.members and\nfriends turned out in masses to\nthe invitations extended and en\njoyed greetings that were given\nfijom different organizations, and\nGrand officers that were present.\nIt seemed like \u201cold timeM\u201d\nwhen the Calumet Post No. 9t)\nAmerican Legion celebrated their\nHf/th birthday Sunday evening\nin the Legion home, 2384 Broad\nway. James W. Thomas, served\nas master o\u2018f ceremonies with'\nAdjuant Todd chairman of pro\ngram. The Auxiliary presented\na large beautiful birthday cake\nto the Post with the members\n\u25a0with their president, Mrs. Anna\nWeber, singing \u201cHappy Birth\nday.\u201d The cake was accepted by\nthe Commander George Palmer\nafter the program a social hour,\nwhere all kinds of sandwiches,\nsalads, coffee and cake were\nserved.\n\nOver 25 women assembled at\nFirst Baptist church Tuesday\nmorning for the all day Re\nIegious Institute which was held\n\u2018by Ithe general missionary of\nFinft Baptist church. The meet\ning was held in the Charles\nllawkins auditorium, with Mrs.\nMaggie Shipman, first vice pre\nsident as instructor. The course\nstudied was Winfred E. Powell's\nbook \u201cThe Growth of Christian\nPersonality\u201d, under original na\nture sub topics were discussed\n(l) \u201cWhat is Meant by Original\nNature?\u201d (2) \u201cTypes of Orginal\nTendences,\u201d (3) \u201cThe Mechan\nism of Man,\u201d (4) \u201cWhat are the\nCharacteristic of Instincts?\u201d and\nf5) \u201cThe Attitude of the Teach\ner.\u201d\nAlso the topic of \u201cWith what\nequipment do pupils begin\nlife*\u201d sub-topic were divided into\nten which were discussed. The\nnoon hour as fellowship over\ncoffee and sandwiches and cake.\nThe afternoon session was de\nvoted to the main topic of the\n\u201cGrowth of Christian Personal\nity.\u201d Everyone who attended\nwas so enriched with the in\nformation that they have asked\nthat the Institute be held quar\nterly for enlightment on Re\nligious work. Mrs. Shipman was\ncommended highly for her very\nefficient manner of out lining\nthe work. Mrs. Wflla O\u2019Dell,\ngeneral president.\nThe Queen Esther Grand Chap\nter, Order of Eastern Star of\nA. M. 'and E. M. of the State\nnf Indiana set up a new Chapter\nThursday, March 20 in the\nMasonic Hall* 1525 Adams\nstreet. The Grand officers .n',L\nwere present were: Royal Grand\nMatron, Mrs. Grace M. Porter;\nGrand State Deputy Matron,\nMrs: Elizabeth WilTiams; Grand\nState Treasurer, Mrs. Bessie A.\nHenderson; Gand Master of\nSlate Mttsonic Lodges, A. F.\nGraves. The new Chapter was\ninstituted with IS members. The\nfollowing officers were selected;\nWorthy matron, Mrs. Bessie\nA. Henderson; worthy patron,\nT P. Ilcarn; associate matroa, 1\nMrs. Eliza Hudson; treasurer,\nMrs. Josephine Hearn; secretary,\nMrs. Virginia Graves; conduc\ntress, Mrs. Lillie M. Barnett;\nassociate conductress, Mrs. I.. B.\nPinkin, other members are:\nMesdames Louise Lusk, Zephy\nHarris, Alice Williams, Thelma\nM. Dobb, Mattie McRae. Ida\nSpeller, Izora Fullilove, Doris\nQuarrells, Annie F, Moss,\nGeorgia Mae Wade, Maggie L.\nYoung, Ernestine Thoma^ and\n.Edna Whiteside.'\nJ The officers were installed by\nGrand Deputy Mrs. E. Williams.\nThe next meeting will be April\n1, at 1525 Adams street at 11\nin the morning.\n\nA new club that has been or\nganized known as \u201cThe Anglers\nRod and Re.el Club\u201d presented\nthe first \u201cSpring Tea\u201d Sunday\nMarch 23 in the home of Mr.\nand Mrs. Mack Garrett, 1057\nW. 25tji avenue. The program\nconsisted of group singing, wel\ncome extended by Mrs. John I.\nCampbell, response by Mrs.\nFloyd Templeton, a reading,\n\u201cCreation\u201d given by Mr. Saint\nM. Dunn.\nThe guest speaker was Mr.\nRodney S. Rankins an officer of\ngrassroots opinion\nMILFORD, Ind., MAIL: \u201cA\nfree economy does not move in a\nstraight line, but in curves, up\nand down. At present there is\na downward trend but increased\ndefense spending raising the na\ntional debt ceiling to $280\nbillion, easing of credit and other\nmanipulations are calculated to\nprovide the sagging economy\nwith a shot in the arm. It may\nmean another ride on the merry\ngo-round of inflation.\u201d\nVIRGINIA, Minn., Mfepabi\nDaily News: \u201cIf we can in this\nfast-moving age have solid\neconomic development without\nthe corrosive influence of in\nflation we ought to begin to find\nit out. Unless' we start soon to\ntry we may discover one day\nthat inflation is taken for grant\ned by management, labor and\neverybody else as an inescapable\ncompanion to our economic pro\ni\nLake County Conservation of\nIndiana. Mr. Rankins related\na y interesting historical\nevents of Indiana and discussed\nin details the twelve divisions of\nfishing, hunting and boating. He j\nwarned the members of the many\ndangers in each one of these\nsports. Mrs. George Morow serv\ned as mistress of ceremonies,\nMrs. Etta Walker is the presi\ndent.\n\nI\nThe Sallie .W. Stewart Guild\nwill meet Thursday, April 3 in\nthe home of Mrs. O. L. Johnson,\nvdth the president, Mrs. Mille\nMoran as hostess.\nr\nThe Musical Department of\nFirst Baptist church will present\nthe first appearence of the Ober\nlin College Choir in Gary Mon\nj day night, March 31 in the\nchurch at 7:30 p.m. The public\nis invited.\nThe Usher Board of First\nAME church is having the annual\nSpring tea Sunday, March 30\nat the church at 3:30 p.m.\nThe Celeatha B. Johnson Club\nwill meet Wednesday night, April\n2 in the home of the vice presi\ndent. Mrs. Mary Lee Beckham,\n2340 Washington street at 7\np.b.\nThe A. L. Harris Household\nof; Iiuth No., G707 will meet\nWednesday night at 7 p.m. in\nthe home of Mrs. Ocia P.\nSpraggips, 17GS Van Buren\nstreet.\nMrs. Murril Hanyard was\nhostess to Modern Priscilla Club\nMonday afternoon in her home,\nh.V>4S Madison stret. A large\naaendance turned out that they\nmight hear the great speaker,\nwho was Mrs. Dorothy Long, the\nhead teacher of Norton Park\nschool for Cripple Children,\n131*6 HairrSson bpulevard. She\nshowed movies of the summer\nday camp, and a trip the Crip\npied Children made to the zoo.\nMrs. Holman Evans chairman\ncf education presented a check\nof $75.00 to Mrs. Long from the\nClub, which she was very grate\nful for. The hosteess served a\ndelicious turkey dinner with all\nthe trimmings with creamed\nlemon pie for dessert. The next\nmeeting will be held in the home\nof Mrs.. Bessie Adkins Hender\nson, 2393 Pennsylvania street.\nMrs. H. C. Mayo, president.\n\nMrs. Fannie Chapman of 2553\nWashington street was hostess to\nAlpha Art Club Thursday after\nnoon. Tentative plans were made\nfor the annual Educational Day.\nReports were given from City\nFederation. The hostes served\na delicious dinner.\ngress. Then is hastened the day\nwhen the house of cards will\ncollapse.\u201d\nINDIO, Calif., The Date Palm:\n\u201cincome, necessary is it is, would\nnot be a cureall for the Post\ncffice Department's ills. a The de\npartment has been in a gradually\nworsening mess for many years.\nIt operation has been kicked 'and\nstarved and exploited by politics\nalmost to the point of complete\ndemoralization of its personnel.\nThe decline in the quality of its\nservice is known to everybody\nwho uses th mails.\u201d\nRED CREEK, N. Y., Herald;\n\u201cThe free nations have pooled\ntheir military powers, have armed\nfor war but have not pooled\ntheir brain-power. It is past time\nthey did. And this brain-power\ncan be used or peaceful objec\ntives too, for development of\nmany great things to make life\nbetter, for science has not yet\nreached all its potentialities.\u201d\nRIVERTON, Wyo., Ranger:\n1 \u201cGovernment has grown so large\nthat it is beyond comprehension,\nincapable of self-regulation and\nbent on prepetuation of its\nvarious components. \u201cPeople fepr\nj the thought of the unwieldy\nI monster attaching even one of\nits tentacles onto the public\nj schools, no matter how innocent\nand trivial the initial attachment\nseems to be.\u201d\nGRAFSON, Ky., Journal-En\nquirer: \u201cI applying for divorce,\na Brisbane, Australia, man told\nthe court his wife made him\nsleep in the barn where she\nserved his meals by throwing them\nat him, and that she often parad\ned nude inthe yard. Press report.\nSom women are harder to live\nwith than others.\u201d\nNORWALK, Conn., Hour:\u201c The\nguiding spirit of thq recovery, as\nthe President sees it, is not a\ncrash program by the govern\nment. Rather, the government is\nhading off with enough to en\nThey Fathered The Steel industry\nWilliam Kelly\nWere it not for two inventive geniuses\u2014an Amei\nan Englishman\u2014the \u201cSteel Age\" might not have\ncentury ago.\nWhile steel had been made in small quantities\ncient times, the inventions of William Kelly of\nicon, and\nbegun a\nsince on\nthe Uni\nted States, and Sir henry\nBessemer of England made\nit possible to produce large\ntonnages of steel speedily and\neconomically.\nIt was Kelly and Bessemer\n\u2014thousands of miles apart\u2014\nwho developed almost simul\ntaneously the process of blow\ning air through molten iron\nto remove certain impurities.\nAlthough the English metal\nlurgist Bessemer was honored\nby having the steelmaking\nprocess named after him, it\nis generally conceded that\nWilliam Kelly, a native of\nPittsburgh who moved to Ken\ntucky, conceived the idea in\n1847. A good researcher,\nKelly was a poor businessman\nand neglected to patent his\nprocess.\nBessemer, who had received\nhis English patent on the pro\ncess in 1855, applied for and\nobtained his American patent\nrights in 1856. As soon as\nKelly learned of the Bessemer\npatents he filed a claim of\npriority of invention. In 1857\nKelly was granted a patent\non the process after demon\nstrating the priority of his\ncourage private enterprise. Busi\nness is there \u2018for those who be\nlieve in it and prepare for it.'\nih recovery will be sounder and\nmore lasting that way.\u201d\nWALTHAM, Mass., News\nTribune: \u201cThe talk is of tax\ncuts as a pump-priming device\nat the national level to cope with\nthe recession. This is deficit\nfinancing of the most extreme\nnatre, in which all possibility of\na pay-as-you-go policy is chucked\nout the wondow. How can the\ngovernment expect its citizens to\nbe thrifty when it gives not heed\nto tomorow\u2019s bills?\u201d\nNEW PHILADELPHIA, Ohio,\nDaily Times: \u2018\u2018The communist\nworld does a great deal of blat\nant advertising of its alleged\ncharms for the masses of human\nity.\n\u201cIn a recent CBS interview,\nMayor Willy Brandt of West\nBerlin, said that every day 300\nto 500| East Germans cross into\nWest Berlin as refugees. \u00a3?ince\n1950 the stream has mounted to\nmore than one million. If Com\nmunist lands are such a magni\nficent haven for humanity, why\ndon\u2019t people stay, You\u2019ll never\nset the answer to that in the\nKremlin\u2019s advs.\u201d\nj BEDFORD, Ind., Daily Times\nj Mail: \u201cEducation is the most\nselfish thing in the world. The\n[only person who can give it to\nyou is you. Teachers can lead,\nsuggest, cajole, even browbeat,\nhut they can\u2019t make you learn.\nThat you do* alone.\u201d\nj -<S>-\nSavery took the \u2018\u20181\u201d out of\n\u201cslavery.\u201d Savery Library at\nTalladega College, one of the 33\nindependent mmbr icoUeges of\nthe United Negro College Fund,\nwas named for an ex-slave,\nWilliam Savery. Freed at the\nend of the Civil War, he worked\nas a carpenter; helped construct\nthe college\u2019s first building; be\ni came a college trustee. Long ago\nl Savery worked to give his child\nren jindgr andchildren a place to\nto school. Fou can help boys\nand girls go to coliege Today.\nGive to the UNCF.\nh'*\u2019\nSir Henry Bessemer\nclaim to the satisfaction of the\nU. S. Commissioner. Further\nevidence of the vpi;r,:'\nthe patents ran cut in loir.\nKelly\u2019s patent was extended\nand Bessemer\u2019s U. S. patent\nwas denied.\nThe Bessemer converter\nwas slow in being introduce i,\nbut once it was put to use ik>\ntremendous impact on steel\nmaking wTas quickly evident\nWhere only about 3,000 tor\nof steel was made by tin\nBessemer process in 1867, by\n1888, the year Kelly die\nproduction by this procc\nwas nearly 3,000,000 tons\nyear.\nInvention of the Bessenrm:\nconverter process had a pio\nnounced effect on life in our\ncountry. As the steel industry\ngrew, so grew agriculture,\nmanufacturing, transporta\ntion, construction, communi\ncations and the other elements\nof our industrial life. It might\nbe said that here in America\nthe Kelly-Bessemer process\nbecame the key for opening\na new and better life for all\nof us.","height":"24608","width":"16624"}}
